'''Ana María Arroyo Mariscal''' (31 July 1923 – 28 March 1995) better known as '''Ana Mariscal''' was a classic [[Spain|Spanish]] film [[actress]], [[Film director|director]], [[screenwriter]] and [[film producer]]. She also acted in Argentinean films. She was involved in well over 50 films between 1940 and 1968, frequently starring in films she also wrote and directed. She is iconic to 1940s and 50s Spanish cinema. Her brother [[Luis Arroyo (film director)|Luis Arroyo]] (1915–1956) was also an actor and film director.

== Early Career and Education ==
Mariscal was born in Madrid in 1923 to a middle-class family. Her father owned a furniture store and a theater that would provide Mariscal much of her early exposure to acting. While occasionally appearing in theater productions with her brother, Mariscal intended to go to university to study mathematics. She decided to pursue acting after being incidentally cast in her first film role.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6HctKgK5lsC&pg=PA186&lpg=PA186&dq=ana+mariscal&source=bl&ots=jpaPFues5z&sig=u7Vvi3ZJI5wsckBucKzaorhQg0A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNl8Xg29DeAhVkMn0KHczICVY4ChDoATAJegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=ana%20mariscal&f=false|title=Heroines Without Heroes: Reconstructing Female and National Identities in European Cinema, 1945-1951|last=Siehlohr|first=Ulrike|date=2000-03-01|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780304702503|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NnMqzBu1vH4C&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=ana+mariscal+career&source=bl&ots=HuljnwkQNP&sig=bOudjXdKCUitYosKwVQaxVaqB7E&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-m533ntPeAhXollQKHf8LCz0Q6AEwBHoECAUQAQ#v=onepage&q=ana%20mariscal%20career&f=false|title=Feminist Discourse and Spanish Cinema: Sight Unseen|last=Martin-Márquez|first=Susan|last2=Martin-Marquez|first2=Assistant Professor in the Department of Spanish and Portuguese Susan|date=1999|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198159797|language=en}}</ref>

== Career ==
Ana Mariscal began her career after accompanying her actor brother Luis Arroyo to an audition for ''El Ultimo Husar''. Almost by chance, she was noticed by the director [[Luis Marquina]] and cast in the film. This would start a prolific career in acting and directing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cvc.cervantes.es/el_rinconete/anteriores/junio_01/08062001_02.htm|title=CVC. Rinconete. Cine y televisión. Ana Mariscal: una mujer marcada, por José Ignacio Pernas.|website=cvc.cervantes.es|language=es|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref>

Over the next decade, Mariscal would star in over twenty films, becoming a household name in Spain. A few notable films from this time include ''[[The Queen's Flower Girl]]'', ''[[Raza (film)|Raza]], [[A Shadow at the Window|A Shadow at the Window,]]'' and ''[[The Princess of the Ursines]]''. After a decade of typecast roles<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2003/04/17/andalucia/1050531735_850215.html|title=Reportaje {{!}} Una pionera del cine español|last=País|first=Ediciones El|date=2003-04-17|work=El País|access-date=2018-11-16|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>, Mariscal would start her own production company called BOSCO and begin writing and directing her own works.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kGikCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA548&lpg=PA548&dq=ana+mariscal+bosco+productions&source=bl&ots=HgsWYG5eTk&sig=914MTCkzVgv1LNJbdO42_7Z5eiI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjDqYbTvNjeAhWHjFQKHc42DQUQ6AEwCnoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=ana%20mariscal%20bosco%20productions&f=false|title=Women Screenwriters: An International Guide|last=Nelmes|first=Jill|last2=Selbo|first2=Jule|date=2015-09-29|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137312372|language=en}}</ref> She made her directorial debut with ''[[Segundo López|Segundo Lopez]],'' a film she also wrote and starred in. It was a critically well-received comedy with [[Italian neorealism|Italian Neo-realist]] influences. She would later direct her esteemed work ''[[They Fired with Their Lives|They fired with their lives]]'' that deals with the [[Spanish Civil War]]; an event Mariscal herself lived through during her childhood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmotech.com/v2/ES/FX_RevistaEditorial.asp?ID=2543|title=Filmotech.com - Revista de Cine - ReportajesYO TAMBIÉN QUIERO SER DIRECTOR . De delante a detrás de la cámara|website=www.filmotech.com|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref>

In her later career she would shift between film, television, and theater pursuits, still using her production company to fund her projects. During this period she would direct or be involved with ''Occidente y sabotaje,'' ''El Camino,'' and ''The Other Woman.'' She would soon begin teaching classes at the IIEC (Institute of Investigations and Cinematographic Experiences) while still balancing acting and directing jobs. She would eventually recede from the world of film making and dedicate her time entirely to the study of literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cvc.cervantes.es/el_rinconete/anteriores/junio_01/08062001_02.htm|title=CVC. Rinconete. Cine y televisión. Ana Mariscal: una mujer marcada, por José Ignacio Pernas.|website=cvc.cervantes.es|language=es|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref>

Just a few months before her death, She would receive the Gold Medal for Merit in the Fine Arts in 1995.<ref>https://www.boe.es/boe/dias/1995/01/04/pdfs/A00273-00273.pdf</ref> She is buried in the Cementerio de la Almudena<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7702997/ana-mariscal|title=Ana Mariscal (1923 - 1995)|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

