{{Infobox writer <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].--> | name = Aïcha Fofana | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1957 | birth_place = [[Bamako]], [[Mali]] | death_date = 10 August 2003 | death_place = Bamako, Mali | resting_place = | occupation = Translator and author | language = | nationality = Malian | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = Lycée Notre-Dame | alma_mater = [[Sorbonne]] | period = | genre = <!-- or: | genres = --> | subject = <!-- or: | subjects = --> | movement = | notableworks = ''Mariage: on copie''; ''La fourmilière: roman''; ''Excellence on fait le ménage'' | spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = --> | partner = <!-- or: | partners = --> | children = | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }}
'''Aïcha Aminata Laïla Fofana''' (1957 – 10 August 2003) was a Malian translator and author. With ''Mariage: on copie'' (1994), she became the first woman in [[Mali]] to publish a novel.<ref name="Boyd-BuggsScott2003">{{cite book|last1=Boyd-Buggs|first1=Debra|last2=Scott|first2=Joyce Hope|title=Camel Tracks: Critical Perspectives on Sahelian Literatures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OU5smBgGku0C&pg=PA271|year=2003|publisher=Africa World Press|isbn=978-0-86543-757-9|pages=271–}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aflit.arts.uwa.edu.au/FofanaAichaEng.html|title=Aïcha Fofana|publisher=University of Western Australia|accessdate=4 February 2016|language=}}</ref> A women's rights activist, her writings are aimed at improving the social conditions for women in Mali.<ref name="ImperatoImperato2008"/>
==Biography== Born in [[Bamako]], Mali, in 1957, Aïcha Fofana was the daughter of Bénitiéni Fofana (1928–1991), who served as Mali's Minister of Health. After her primary school education in Bamako and in [[Bordeaux]], France, she attended the Lycée Notre-Dame in [[Niger]]. She went on to study languages, first at the [[Sorbonne]], then at the [[University of Mannheim]], Germany, and at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]. With her command of French, German and English, she subsequently worked as a translator and interpreter.<ref name="Boyd-BuggsScott2003"/>
Her first novel ''Mariage: on copie'' probes the conventional views of Malian women, telling the story of four of them who experience different problems owing to their varied ethnic backgrounds and status. By describing how the women resolve their marital problems, the novel sets out to show that Malian society is moving in the right direction.<ref name="Boyd-BuggsScott2003"/> Her second novel ''La fourmilière'' (The Anthill) was published posthumously in 2006.<ref name="ImperatoImperato2008">{{cite book|last1=Imperato|first1=Pascal James|last2=Imperato|first2=Gavin H.|title=Historical Dictionary of Mali|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zf6xAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA117|year=2008|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6402-3|pages=117–}}</ref> It brings out the difficulties of Malian society as represented by the life of a large family. Her title is inspired by social structures which can be compared to those of a colony of ants.<ref name=volet>{{cite web|url=http://motspluriels.arts.uwa.edu.au/MP1299fofana.html|title=A l'ecoute d'Aïcha Fofana: Un entretien avec Aïcha Fofana, romancière et femme de théâtre|author=Volet, Jean-Marie|publisher=University of Western Australia|date=July 1999|accessdate=4 February 2016 |language=French}}</ref>
Frustrated by the time taken to have books published, Fofana decided to turn to the theatre where she could rely on communicating her ideas much more quickly. In April 1997, her first play ''Excellence on fait le ménage'' was presented at Bamako's Cultural Centre. As it was critical of political corruption, it caused quite a stir, both among the actors and those who came to see it.<ref name=volet/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aflit.arts.uwa.edu.au/Fofanaexcellence.html|title=Excellence on fait le ménage|publisher=University of Western Australia|accessdate=4 February 2016 |language=}}</ref> Her second play, ''L'Africaine de Paris no 2'', presented the following year, tells the story of a Malian who marries a local woman only to discover that his first wife, also an African whom he married in Paris, comes to claim him as her husband, upsetting the family environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aflit.arts.uwa.edu.au/Fofanaafricaine.html|title=L'Africaine de Paris no 2|publisher=University of Western Australia|date=12 August 1998|accessdate=4 February 2016 |language=French}}</ref>
Fofana is also remembered as a courageous advocate of women's rights. In 1998, she was a founding member of the [[Association Malienne des Droits de l'Homme|Malian Association of Human Rights]]. Her writings are often centred on improving social conditions for African women.<ref name="ImperatoImperato2008"/>
Aïcha Fofana died unexpectedly in Bamako on 16 August 2003.<ref name="ImperatoImperato2008"/>
